Carbon-carbon atoms in GQD are ~1.43 Å [54,55] and when single O/S/N/B is doped in COG, a distortion is produced with length of bond between C-X(O/S/N/B) shifted (Fig. S2). Bond lengths, C-X = (O/S/N/B), C-X = (O/S/N/B) and C-X = (O/S/N/B) are 1.5249/1.7831/1.4290/1.5299, 1.4651/1.7753/1.4199/1.5027 Å and 1.4815/1.7801/1.4149/1.5099 Å, different from GQD [56]. The C-X(O/S/N/B)-C, C-X(O/S/N/B)-C and C-X(O/S/N/B)-C bond angles are 118.7/100.9/118.6/119.8 Å, 120.5/101.0/121.4/120.1° and 117.0/101.6/120.0/120.2°, respectively [57,58]. COG-O/N/B geometry reveals the pi-electron planar sp2 structure with delocalization. For COGS, the bond length CS are high resulting in structural distortion compared to other doping which results in rising of S atom from surface of nanocluster plane (Fig. S2) which is due to larger radius of sulphur [59]. The adsorption energy was calculated in order to understand the mechanism of binding of DPH over nanoclusters. Fig. 2
                         shows the DPH structures over clusters (where DPH initially put in parallel mode with the nanocluster) after optimization. Following optimization, DPH get adsorbed at edges of COG-S and COG-B where the carbonyl ring group of DPH is reoriented away in a tilted fashion on the side of GQD. For others, adsorption of DPH is in a tilted manner on the surface of GQD with carbonyl ring oxygen atom of DPH near to the surface of GQD. After optimization, energy of adsorption is measured by subtracting from total energy of combined system (DPH over (G/COG/COG-X(X = O, S, N, B))) clusters, the amount of individual energy of DPH and (G/COG/COG-X(X = O, S, N, B)). The energy of DPH adsorption over O-GQD, B-GQD and N-GQD are −3.341, −3.672 and −3.608 eV (Table 1
                        ). DPH's energy over O/B/N-GQD is greater than that over other nanoclusters (0.226 eV for G-DPH, −2.2979 eV for COG-DPH and −2.761 eV for COG-S-DPH) [60]. The greater strength of adsorption in O/B/N-GQD is due to O/B/N being more electronegative than sulphur and carbon atoms. The mechanism of adsorption will be explored more specifically by the study of the electronic properties.
